An array is a collection of elements (values or variables), all of the same data type, stored in contiguous memory locations.
Arrays are used to store multiple values in a single variable instead of declaring separate variables for each value.
Example of an Array:
int mark1 = 85;
int mark2 = 90;
int mark3 = 78;
int mark4 = 88;
int mark5 = 92;
You can use an array:
int marks[5] = {85, 90, 78, 88, 92};
Here:

int → data type of array elements

marks → name of the array

[5] → size of the array (number of elements)

{85, 90, 78, 88, 92} → initial values of the array
Array Declaration (General Syntax):
data_type array_name[array_size];
Example:
int numbers[10];  // declares an integer array with 10 elements
